# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bakso
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bakso/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:bakso/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:bakso/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:bakso/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:bakso/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:bakso/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:bakso/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:bakso/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:bakso/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:bakso/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:bakso/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:bakso/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:bakso/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:bakso/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:bakso/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:bakso/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:bakso/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:bakso/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:bakso/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:bakso/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:bakso/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:bakso/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:bakso/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:bakso/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:bakso/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:bakso/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:bakso/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:bakso/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:bakso/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:bakso/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:bakso/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:bakso/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:bakso/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:bakso/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:bakso/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:bakso/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:bakso/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bakso/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:bakso/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:bakso/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:bakso/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:bakso/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:bakso/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:bakso/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:bakso/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:bakso/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:bakso/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:bakso/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:bakso/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:bakso/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:bakso/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:bakso/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:bakso/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:bakso/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:bakso/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:bakso/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:bakso/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:bakso/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:bakso/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:bakso/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:bakso/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:bakso/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:bakso/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:bakso/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:bakso/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:bakso/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:bakso/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:bakso/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:bakso/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:bakso/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:bakso/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:bakso/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:bakso/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:bakso/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:bakso/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:bakso/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:bakso/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:bakso/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:bakso/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:bakso/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:bakso/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:bakso/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:bakso/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:bakso/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:bakso/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:bakso/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:bakso/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:bakso/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:bakso/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:bakso/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:bakso/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:bakso/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:bakso/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:bakso/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:bakso/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:bakso/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:bakso/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:bakso/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:bakso/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:bakso/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:bakso/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:bakso/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:bakso/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:bakso/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:bakso/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:bakso/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:bakso/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:bakso/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:bakso/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:bakso/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:bakso/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:bakso/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:bakso/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:bakso/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:bakso/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:bakso/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:bakso/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:bakso/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:bakso/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:bakso/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:bakso/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:bakso/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:bakso/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:bakso/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:bakso/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:bakso/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:bakso/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Currently, there are no alcohol bans being enforced in Indonesia, with the exception of Aceh.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since 2014, anyone found consuming alcohol or breaching the codes on moral conduct, whether residents or visitors to Aceh, could face between six and nine cane lashes.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In other parts of Indonesia, to appease the Islamic parties and pressure groups, the government agreed to apply mild restriction measures on alcohol, which includes high taxation and limited bans.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia is among the countries that apply high taxes on imported alcoholic beverages; in 2015, import tax on alcohol jumped to 150%.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in 2015, the Indonesian government banned the sale of alcohol from minimarkets and small shops, with the exception of Bali province, though sale was allowed in supermarkets, restaurants, bars, clubs and hotels.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, in more cosmopolitan Indonesian cities like Jakarta, Medan and Surabaya, and also in tourism hotspots such as Bali, Yogyakarta and Batam, alcoholic beverages are readily available, yet with higher prices, owing to the high tax applied upon alcoholic beverages.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2016, Indonesian Malt Beverage Producers Association (GIMMI) called the House of Representatives to draft for comprehensive regulations on the chain of production and the marketing of alcoholic beverages, instead of total prohibition.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since ancient times, local alcoholic beverages were developed by natives in the archipelago.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some panels in 9th century Borobudur bas-reliefs depicted drink vendors, *warung* (small restaurant), and there is a panel depicting a building with people drinking (possibly alcoholic beverages), dancing and having fun, seeming to depict a tavern or lodging house.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to a Chinese source, Yingya Shenglan (c.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] 15th century) the people of Java in Majapahit kingdom drank wine made from palm sap called *tuak* (palm wine).
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, by the 16th century Islam began to supplant Hinduism and Buddhism as the major religion in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since then, as a Muslim-majority country, Indonesian Muslims share Islamic dietary laws that prohibit alcoholic beverages.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, the local alcohol-drinking culture still survives, at least among less-religious members of society and among the non-Muslim community.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Certain ethno-cultural regions which are predominantly Christian are known for their affinity to alcohol-drinking traditions; such as the Batak, Torajan, Minahasan, Ambonese and Papuan.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia has its own traditional alcoholic beverages prepared by fermenting rice grain, gluten, sugar palm sap, and coconuts.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to culinary expert William Wongso, the culture of drinking distilled alcohol was never strong in Indonesia, with only a few regions having developed it.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Batak community in North Sumatra, *tuak* (palm liquor) is a compulsory drink in the celebrations and became a tradition in the community.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Batak tribes are predominantly of Christian Protestant faith, yet some of its clans are Muslim.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] A traditional Batak bar serving *tuak* is called a *lapo tuak*.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Toraja lands of South Sulawesi, their version of *tuak* — made from fermented sugar palm sap, is called *ballo*.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Torajan traditional ceremonies, rituals and celebrations, *ballo* is always served, either as a prerequisite for the ritual; as an offering for ancestral spirits, as well as for drinks for guests.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Ballo* is also commonly consumed by the neighboring Bugis ethnic group.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Minahasa region of North Sulawesi, an almost identical palm liquor, also made from sugar palm sap, is called *saguer*.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Nusa Tenggara and Maluku Islands the people also drink palm wine, locally known as *sopi*.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in the Minahasa region, the people drink a highly alcoholic drink called *cap tikus* (lit.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Cap tikus* is made from distilled *saguer* or *sopi* (palm wine), which increases its alcohol content.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The origin of *cap tikus* brand is unclear.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is suggested that circa 1820s, prior to the 1830 Java War, the KNIL Minahasan legion found and bought distilled *saguer* or *sopi* sold in blue bottles embossed with the image of mouse sold by a Chinese merchant in Fort Amsterdam in Manado.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Today however, because of poor regulation on alcohol production in this region, this traditional home-made *cap tikus* industry is considered as an illegal beverage, due to the high prevalence of mortal alcohol poisoning.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bottled *brem bali* (Balinese rice wine) and *arrack* are popular beverages in the Hindu-majority island of Bali.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem* is a brownish colored liquor with 5% alcohol.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] For Balinese people it has a religious significance too.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem*, *arak* and *tuak* are required for *tabuhan* (offerings) to the gods.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Solo, Central Java, *ciu*, a local adaptation of Chinese wine, made from cider molasses of sugarcane is well known.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is linked to Solo's history as a sugar plantation and production center in colonial times.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Dutch Colonial state was established in Indonesia in the 1800s.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The colonial Dutch brought their European drinking culture to the East Indies, most prominently with beer.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Heineken beer company established its brewery factory in Surabaya in 1929 during the Dutch colonial rule of Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] By the 1960s, Indonesians developed their own local brands of beer, which included Bintang Beer (nationalized from Heineken) and Anker Beer.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In April 2019, the East Nusa Tenggara provincial government supported the legal aspect of production and distribution of sopi, a local traditional alcoholic beverage.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] This policy is very likely to make sopi the first fully supported alcoholic product by the local government in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] A Presidential regulation signed by Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono in 2013 gave legal cover to distribution of alcohol, it classified alcoholic beverages in Indonesia in three categories.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Drinks having an alcohol percentage less than 5% (A class), 5%–20% (B class) and more than 20% (C class).
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] It was replacement of the 1997 decree after the Supreme Court abolished it following appeals from hard-line religious groups like the Islamic Defenders Front.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The 2012 court ruling came after a draft bill proposed by the United Development Party (PPP) to completely ban the sale, production and consumption of alcohol in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, the 2013 presidential regulation was welcomed by travel agencies in the wake of the harmful effects of the proposed draft on tourism.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Prices of wine and spirits in Indonesia increased by 140.5% and 154.4% respectively between 2009 and 2014.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2015 the government further hiked the import tariff on wine and spirits which nearly doubled the price of alcoholic beverages.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some foreign companies which sell alcohol in Indonesia are Diageo, Pernod Ricard, Remy Cointreau and Bacardi.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] PT Multi Bintang is the largest domestic brewery of Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] As per market experts, because of various regulations, alcohol sales are declining in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bintang Beer of Multi Bintang brewery is the largest selling beer of Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Multi Bintang is a subsidiary of Heineken Asia Pacific.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2011, Bintang Beer won the Gold Medal for the Lager Beer Category and was awarded 'Champion Beer 2011' at the world's class beer competition, the Brewing Industry International Award (BIIA 2011) in London.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2014 Bintang Radler was introduced which was the first flavored beer produced domestically in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other major beer producers are Delta Djakarta known for its Anker Beer, and PT Bali Hai Brewery Indonesia known for its Bali Hai.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia also produces other brands, including San Miguel Beer and Asahi beer, under license.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Diageo manufactures Smirnoff and Captain Morgan products in Bali, which qualifies both brands for classification as locally produced spirits.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The high prices of alcohol beverages in Indonesia, caused by high taxation and restrictions, has led to cases of illegal alcohol in the country.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] As the legal and imported alcoholic beverages become unaffordable, locals turn to illegal bootlegged alcohol for a cheaper drink.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illegal alcoholic drinks are known in Indonesian as *alkohol oplosan* (lit.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] "solved alcohol") and account for over 80% of the alcohol consumed in Indonesia.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illicitly produced liquors which are traditionally home-made, are considered illegal by Indonesian law, due to the high incidence of deadly alcohol poisoning.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] The *lapen* liquor from Yogyakarta for example, is made from industrial alcohol of 85% volume mixed with water with a 1:4 or 5 alcohol to water ratio; then mixed with fruit essence as a flavoring agent.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2010, 16 people died and 5 *lapen* sellers were arrested in Yogyakarta, due to alcohol poisoning and illicit alcohol production.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] In September 2010, three Russian Sukhoi fighter technicians died in Makassar from methanol poisoning in their drinks.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Yogyakarta residents were again affected by badly made alcohol in 2016.
[src:bakso/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other traditionally made alcoholic spirits such as Solo's *ciu*, Manado's *cap tikus*, and some Balinese *arrack* are known as illegal alcohol, also due to the high incidence of alcohol poisoning.
[src:bakso/aloo-chaat] It can be served as a snack, a side dish or a light meal.
[src:bakso/aloo-chaat] It is made from boiled and fried cubed potatoes served with chat masala.
[src:bakso/aloo-chaat] It is a versatile dish that has many regional variations.
[src:bakso/aloo-chaat] The word *alu* means potatoes in Hindi and the word *chat* is derived from the Hindi word *chatna*, which means 'tasting'.
[src:bakso/aloo-chaat] Thus, 'alu chat' means a savory potato snack.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] Because of the broad geographical distribution of Indian people throughout the world, a number of variations on this dish exist.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] In Maharashtra, a popular version of aloo tikki is served with a spicy curry and various chutneys.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] It is called ragda pattice and is sold at various chaat stalls throughout the city and especially on Chowpatti Beach.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] The aloo tikki in this region is made of mainly locally grown spices such as turmeric, whereas in Bangalore, more coriander is used.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] In the United Kingdom, vegetable tikki is available from delicatessen counters at various shops.
[src:bakso/aloo-tikki] Some North Indian dhabas or café-style eateries will sandwich the aloo in bread.
[src:bakso/bakso] As most Indonesians are Muslims and observe *halal* dietary laws, *bakso* is usually made from beef, chicken, or a mixture of beef and chicken.
[src:bakso/bakso] In non-Muslim majority areas, such as in the Chinatowns of major cities and on the Hindu-majority island of Bali, pork *bakso* might be found.
[src:bakso/bakso] Traditionally the beef surimi paste or dough is made into balls by hand and boiled in hot water.
[src:bakso/bakso] After the meat is done, the meatballs are dried and served or refrigerated for later use.
[src:bakso/bakso] Pre-cooked *bakso* are usually displayed in the windows of street vendor carts.
[src:bakso/bakso] The name *bakso* originated from *bak-so* (肉酥, Pe̍h-ōe-jī: *bah-so͘*), the Hokkien pronunciation for "fluffy meat" or "minced meat".
[src:bakso/bakso] This suggests that bakso has Indonesian Chinese cuisine origin.
[src:bakso/bakso] Chinese influence is apparent in Indonesian food, such as *bakmi*, *mie ayam*, *pangsit*, *mie goreng*, *kwetiau goreng*, *bakso*, and *lumpia*.
[src:bakso/bakso] Indeed, bakso texture is quite similar to Chinese beef balls, which are quite fluffy and have a homogenous texture.
[src:bakso/bakso] Although *bakso* has a Chinese Hokkien origin name, culinary experts suggest that it is likely that *bakso* was a mixture of culinary influences back in the colonial Dutch East Indies.
[src:bakso/bakso] Also in Indonesian, the term *bola daging* often refers to the Western or European style of meatballs, which is different in texture and elasticity compared to bakso.
[src:bakso/bakso] For example, Swedish meatballs are translated as *bola daging Swedia* in Indonesian.
[src:bakso/bakso] The soup and the noodles probably originated in China, but the meatball may have come from the Dutch, who colonized Indonesia in the 19th century.
[src:bakso/bakso] Despite its possible Chinese origin, *bakso* seems to have undergone localization, especially into Chinese Indonesian and Javanese cuisine.
[src:bakso/bakso] Today, most of the *bakso* vendors are native Javanese from Wonogiri (a town near Solo) and Malang.
[src:bakso/bakso] *Bakso Solo* and *Bakso Malang* are the most popular variants; the name comes from the city it comes from, Solo in Central Java and Malang in East Java.
[src:bakso/bakso] *Bakso Solo* is usually served with yellow noodles and rice vermicelli in beef broth, while *Bakso Malang* usually is enriched with tofu and crispy fried wonton.
[src:bakso/bakso] In Malang, *bakso bakar* (roasted bakso) is also popular.
[src:bakso/bakso] In Bandung, West Java, there is a type of bakso called bakso cuanki, which is similar to bakso Malang.
[src:bakso/bakso] It can contain various types of bakso ingredients; such as bakso aci, siomay dumpling, boiled wonton, fried wonton, and fried bakso, served with scallion and broth soup.
[src:bakso/bakso] Indonesia has developed numerous bakso variants, usually differing in shape, size, texture, ingredients, and fillings.
[src:bakso/bakso] Bakso stalls usually served bottles of sauces, condiments, additions, and garnishing.
[src:bakso/bakso] Clients may add these condiments according to their personal preferences.
[src:bakso/bakso] The traveling meatball vendor is often associated with intelligence undercover activity.
[src:bakso/bakso] On social media, there are also many memes depicting meatball vendors communicating through walkie-talkies.
[src:bakso/bakso] According to Ridlwan Habib, an intelligence observer, the profession of mobile food traders such as meatball workers is often used by members of the Detective or Densus 88 to spy on terrorist activities or other suspicious criminal activities.
[src:bakso/bakso] Similar meatball dishes can be found in other Southeast Asian cuisines, such as those in Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, and Singapore, as well as Chinese-style meatballs.
[src:bakso/bakso] The dish is also similar to Vietnamese noodle soup with meatballs, *phở bò viên*.
[src:bakso/bakso] In Vietnam, *Phở* means noodle soup while *Bò Viên* is meatballs.
[src:bakso/bakso] Phở Bò Viên is one of the versions of Pho dishes in Vietnam.
[src:bakso/bakso] It has been considered as the national dish of Vietnam.
[src:bakso/bakso] In Malaysia and Singapore, there is a similar meatball soup called *bebola daging*, which is a Malay translation of "meatball".
[src:bakso/bakso] Many recipes of *bebola daging* in Malaysia and Singapore are derived from either Western (Indian or European) or Eastern (Chinese) meatballs, such as *bebola daging Masala* which is derived from Indian cuisine influence.
[src:bakso/bakso] In the Philippines, meatballs are called *almondigas* or *bola-bola*, and are usually served in a misua noodle soup with toasted garlic, squash, and pork cracklings.
[src:bakso/bakso] *Bola-bolas* are also stewed or pan-fried until golden brown.
